DP Direction: 0 → n-1 vs n-1 → 0

There are two common ways to define DP states, and the direction follows the definition.

1) 0 → n-1 (prefix / forward DP)

dp[i] represents the answer up to index i

You must initialize starting states (like dp[0])

Transitions depend on previous indices

Typical in problems like grid DP, knapsack, LIS

2) n-1 → 0 (future / backward DP)

dp[i] represents the answer from index i onward

Base case is at the end (i >= n → 0)

Transitions depend on future indices (i+1, i+2)

Used in stock DP, decision-based problems

Why stock DP uses n-1 → 0
In stock problems, each decision (buy / sell / skip) affects future profit, not past profit.
So the DP state naturally answers: “What is the best profit I can make starting from today?”

Key rule to remember

If DP means “up to i” → fill forward

If DP means “from i onward” → fill backward

This is a modeling choice, not a special rule for stocks.
